---
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#  INSTRUCTIONS FOR CLAUDE (when adding / refreshing a post)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#  1. NEVER change the text the author wrote. No paraphrasing,
#     no rewording, no grammar "fixes", no fact edits.
#
#  2. You MAY (and should) apply SEMANTIC FORMATTING on top of
#     the author's raw text to improve visual readability:
#       • **Bold** key phrases, named entities, metrics (2–5
#         times per paragraph at most — sparingly)
#       • *Italicise* book titles, movie titles, foreign terms,
#         or the author's own emphasis signals
#       • Break long paragraphs into shorter ones (3–5 sentences
#         each) — but only at natural breathing points, and ONLY
#         when the original text clearly has multiple ideas
#       • Convert inline lists into proper bullet lists when the
#         author has written comma-separated enumerations
#       • Wrap code identifiers in `backticks`
#     Do NOT add underlines — markdown underline isn't clean in
#     this theme; prefer bold or italic instead.
#
#  3. Structure: if the post has distinct sections, add `###`
#     subheadings ONLY where the author's own structure calls
#     for them (e.g. rhetorical questions they're answering).
#     Never invent section names the author didn't write.
#
#  4. Images + embeds: follow the patterns below (the <center>
#     + <pre> caption wrapping for images, the <div class="video-
#     container"> pattern for YouTube/Vimeo/etc.).
#
#  5. Frontmatter: set `title`, `date`, `tags`, and `summary`
#     truthfully. `slug` is optional — leave it out unless the
#     filename would produce a weird slug.
#
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#  TEMPLATE — reference for every supported feature in a post.
#
#  This file is NOT published. Its extension (.md.example) hides
#  it from the posts registry (which globs *.md only). Rename to
#  `.md` — or copy-paste the sections into a new post file — and
#  it will appear on the site automatically, sorted by `date`.
#
#  Filename convention: `YYYY-MM-DD-short-slug.md`
#  The leading date prefix is stripped from the URL; the rest is
#  the slug. So `2026-05-01-cool-thing.md` → `/p/cool-thing`.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
title: Everything a Post Can Do
date: 2026-05-01
slug: everything-a-post-can-do       # optional — auto-derived from filename
tags: [reference, template, media]   # optional — rendered as chips
summary: A kitchen-sink example showing every supported feature — headings, images, videos, code, quotes, tables, and more.
draft: true                          # optional — drafts are hidden in production
cover: /images/cover.jpg             # optional — future use, currently unused
---

A leading paragraph sits right below the frontmatter. **Bold**, *italic*, and
`inline code` all work. Links look like [this](https://abhj.github.io).

## Level-2 headings divide major sections

This is body text. Keep paragraphs short — 3–5 sentences typically reads best
on screen. The modern theme styles `<h2>` at 1.7rem in Montserrat 600 with
generous top margin for breathing room.

### Level-3 headings for subsections

Level-3 headings are 1.35rem in the modern theme — same font family, smaller
size, identical top rhythm. Use these for clear topic shifts within a section.

#### Level-4 when you really need a fourth tier

Rarely needed. 1.12rem.

---

## Images — three supported styles

### 1. Plain Markdown (simplest, left-aligned, full width up to container)

![A simple caption that shows on hover](https://picsum.photos/800/400)

### 2. Centered with a caption underneath (raw HTML)

<center>
  <img src="https://picsum.photos/600/400" alt="Scenic shot" width="70%" />
  <br />
  <pre>A subtle caption, rendered in monospace.</pre>
</center>

### 3. Reference a local asset

Drop an image into `public/images/` in the project, then reference it as:

<img src="/abj-blogs/images/my-photo.jpg" alt="My photo" width="60%" />

> Note the `/abj-blogs/` prefix — that's required because the site is served
> under that base path on GitHub Pages.

---

## YouTube embeds

Use the `video-container` div pattern — the modern theme's CSS gives any
iframe inside it a rounded 16:9 aspect with a drop shadow automatically.

<div class="video-container">
  <iframe allowfullscreen src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/dQw4w9WgXcQ"></iframe>
</div>

You can stack multiple videos; each renders independently.

<div class="video-container">
  <iframe allowfullscreen src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/0gHNucQqVNo"></iframe>
</div>

### Other embeds work the same way

Any `<iframe>` gets the same treatment — Vimeo, CodePen, Spotify, etc.

<div class="video-container">
  <iframe allowfullscreen src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/76979871"></iframe>
</div>

---

## Code

### Inline

Reference a symbol like `useEffect` or a path like `src/lib/posts.ts` inline —
it renders in a muted monospace chip.

### Fenced block

```javascript
// Javascript — syntax recognised for optional highlighting later
function greet(name) {
	console.log(`Hello, ${name}`);
	return name.length;
}
```

```typescript
// TypeScript
interface Post {
	title: string;
	date: Date;
	tags: string[];
}
```

```bash
# Shell commands
cd ~/Documents/abj-blogs-master
npm run dev
```

```python
# Python — language hint shown after the opening fence
def square(x: int) -> int:
    return x * x
```

---

## Lists

### Unordered

- First item
- Second item
- Third item, with **bold emphasis** inside
- Fourth with a [link](https://example.com)

### Ordered

1. Install the deps
2. Drop a `.md` file into `src/posts/`
3. `npm run dev`
4. Done

### Nested

- Top level
  - Second level
    - Third level
  - Back to second
- Back to first

### Task lists (GFM)

- [x] Written with front-matter
- [x] Rendered via `react-markdown`
- [ ] Publish it

---

## Blockquotes

> A good blockquote is quiet. It should read like the author's voice paused
> for a moment to let someone else speak.

Multi-paragraph quotes:

> First paragraph of the quote.
>
> Second paragraph continues the same thought, preserved by the blank quote
> line between them.

---

## Tables (GFM)

| Feature | Supported | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Markdown headings | ✅ | `#`, `##`, `###`, `####` |
| Images | ✅ | MD syntax or raw `<img>` |
| YouTube / iframes | ✅ | Wrap in `<div class="video-container">` |
| Code blocks | ✅ | Fenced, optional language hint |
| Tables | ✅ | GFM pipe-table syntax |
| Footnotes | ⚠️ | Plugin not wired up yet |

Tables inherit the site's typography and have a thin border per cell.

---

## Horizontal rules

Use three dashes on their own line. They render as a thin divider.

---

## Inline HTML you may also want

Any raw HTML element works (courtesy of `rehype-raw`). Common ones:

- `<br />` — forced line break
- `<hr />` — same as three dashes above
- `<strong>` / `<em>` — same as `**` / `*`
- `<details>` / `<summary>` — collapsible sections

<details>
  <summary>Click to expand (native HTML, no plugin)</summary>

  Content hidden until the summary is clicked.

  - Works
  - Inside
  - Markdown

</details>

---

## Sign-off

Every post ends when you stop writing — no closing boilerplate required.
The article page adds its own footer with a "← All writing" link.
